{"url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/05/opinion/in-london-we-wont-be-intimidated.html?mcubz=0", "publish_date": "2017-06-05", "text": "Photo\n\nTo the Editor:\n\nRe \u201c2 Attacks in London as a Reeling Nation Faces More Terror\u201d (front page, June 4):\n\nI\u2019m a Londoner born and bred and have been a tour guide here for 20 years. I saw your rather over-the-top, scaremongering headline concerning the London attacks.\n\nMany Americans come on my bike tours through London and are the nicest people one could meet. On Sunday, the day after the attacks, I took out a family from Indiana who were not about to hide in their hotel room, too scared to go out. This goes for the majority of tourists and Londoners.\n\nWe had the Irish Republican Army for 30 years bombing the city, and more than 70 years ago it was the Blitz. We aren\u2019t \u201creeling\u201d from the Manchester attack or the one on Saturday at London Bridge. Any loss of life is tragic and causes anger and grief, but not cowardice. We won\u2019t be intimidated, and neither should anyone from the United States thinking of canceling a trip to Europe.\n\nLondon is a very safe place in the great scheme of things \u2014 more so, I would hazard a guess, than a lot of American cities (no offense intended). Also, you\u2019ll be thousands of miles away from Donald Trump!\n\nAdvertisement Continue reading the main story\n\nCHARLIE COUTTS, LONDON\n\nTo the Editor:\n\nI am so saddened by the loss of innocent lives and the many wounded in the London attacks. I couldn\u2019t help thinking of how much more carnage would have occurred if the three terrorists had been armed with automatic weapons instead of knives. Luckily there is more sensible gun control in the United Kingdom than here in the United States.", "type": "article", "title": "Opinion | In London: \u2018We Won\u2019t Be Intimidated\u2019"}